{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98525251-6130-4b1b-be13-b71268a35193","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which fully supports constructor injection. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext + sync init\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous setup (runs per-test)\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test initialization\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SyncTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest v3+:**\n\n- **Constructor** — receives `TestContext` via injection; use for synchronous setup (runs before each test).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — can return `Task` for async setup; runs after the constructor.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`/`[ClassCleanup]`** — for one-time class-level setup (static methods).\n- The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern still works but constructor injection is preferred.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d54b9f7a-23b9-408c-b093-4ca35e407e0b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), you can use constructor injection for `TestContext`. Let me provide the recommended pattern.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, the recommended approach is:\n1. Constructor injection for `TestContext` (instead of the old property-based approach)\n2. `[TestInitialize]` for synchronous per-test setup\n3. `[TestInitialize]` also supports async (returning `Task`)\n4. Constructor for synchronous one-time setup\n5. `IAsyncLifetime` is NOT an MSTest thing — that's xUnit\n\n\n6. `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` handle class-level setup and teardown\n7. `[TestInitialize]` and `[TestCleanup]` handle per-test setup and teardown, both supporting async operations\n\nI'm setting up the pattern with constructor injection for TestContext...","outputTokens":774,"requestId":"6037:20684E:25CF350:2868D66:6A0311E3"},"id":"d5fe68c4-894e-4833-9a4b-123480fec711","timestamp":"2026-05-12T11:41:41.409Z","parentId":"ffcf8820-06e7-4a74-a5ae-3095a6baa868"}
